1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,739
Harry Qiu began learning English as a young boy in Shanghai, China.

2
00:00:07,739 --> 00:00:15,675
Over the years, he became fluent, and later came to the United States for college.

3
00:00:15,675 --> 00:00:25,776
Qiu now attends Dickinson College in the state of Pennsylvania, where he studies international relations.

4
00:00:25,776 --> 00:00:32,891
There, he is learning two more languages – Russian and Japanese.

5
00:00:32,891 --> 00:00:40,736
And through the school, he gets to talk one-on-one with native speakers on Skype.

6
00:00:40,736 --> 00:00:49,408
For example, when he meets with his Japanese partner, Qiu helps his partner practice English.

7
00:00:49,408 --> 00:00:53,456
His partner helps him practice Japanese.

8
00:00:53,456 --> 00:00:57,120
We call this a language exchange.

9
00:00:57,120 --> 00:01:04,245
Such exchanges can be one of the best ways to improve your conversation skills.

10
00:01:04,245 --> 00:01:14,192
Qiu says they have given him the chance to experience the difference between real life conversation and classroom learning.

11
00:01:14,192 --> 00:01:20,859
Colleges and universities are not the only places offering language exchanges.

12
00:01:20,859 --> 00:01:28,853
Today, there are many websites and apps designed to connect language learners around the world.

13
00:01:28,853 --> 00:01:42,896
Popular sites like Conversation Exchange, Lingo Globe, Easy Language Exchange and The Mixxer offer an almost endless number of partners to choose from.

14
00:01:42,896 --> 00:01:50,880
But doing an exchange without knowing what to expect can sometimes lead to wasted time.

15
00:01:50,880 --> 00:01:57,557
So today, we have five tips for how to have a great language exchange.

16
00:01:57,557 --> 00:02:04,608
Experts say the first step is ask yourself some important questions.

17
00:02:04,608 --> 00:02:16,021
Todd Bryant is a language technology specialist who runs The Mixxer, a website with more than 35,000 active users.

18
00:02:16,021 --> 00:02:20,629
The free service began at Dickinson College.

19
00:02:20,629 --> 00:02:26,080
But it is meant for people around the world looking for practice partners.

20
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:34,272
Bryant says the most important question to ask yourself is why you want to learn the language.

21
00:02:34,272 --> 00:02:42,779
People who have a serious reason for learning a language are usually more dependable exchange partners.

22
00:02:42,779 --> 00:02:51,605
These reasons can include, for example, moving to another country or using the language for work.

23
00:02:51,605 --> 00:03:00,907
Less serious reasons might be wanting to meet new people or use the language for an overseas vacation.

24
00:03:00,907 --> 00:03:08,192
Another question to ask yourself, Bryant says, is how much free time you really have.

25
00:03:08,192 --> 00:03:17,403
“And then also think about how much time you're willing to spend on this so you can then find a good match. ‘Are you willing to spend an hour or two more per week to do this?’”

26
00:03:17,403 --> 00:03:21,115
In addition, consider your preferences.

27
00:03:21,115 --> 00:03:26,501
Are you looking for speaking practice or do you prefer written messages?

28
00:03:26,501 --> 00:03:33,824
If you are seeking speaking practice, would you rather have video meetings or meet in person?

29
00:03:33,824 --> 00:03:40,443
Knowing your preferred method will help you choose the right website or app.

30
00:03:40,443 --> 00:03:50,635
Some websites, for example, list people’s cities, so you can easily make plans to meet partners in person. Others do not.

31
00:03:50,635 --> 00:03:57,040
Now, you are ready for tip 2 - finding the right partner.

32
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:05,637
As I said earlier, many of these websites can have hundreds of partners to choose from in the language you want to learn.

33
00:04:05,637 --> 00:04:09,541
So how can you limit your search?

34
00:04:09,541 --> 00:04:16,213
Bryant says, when reading profiles, look for some important signs.

35
00:04:16,213 --> 00:04:30,603
“People who have been on the site and have been active and have a reason to learn the language are much more likely to be good partners than people who have been on the site for a week and don’t really have their profile filled out and haven’t been active and are learning six languages.”

36
00:04:30,603 --> 00:04:37,936
Another thing to keep in mind is that it is better to find at least two exchange partners.

37
00:04:37,936 --> 00:04:44,619
People lead busy lives and one person may not be available every week.

38
00:04:44,619 --> 00:04:54,277
Once you do find a person who seems like a good fit, be clear about what your expectations are in the first email.

39
00:04:54,277 --> 00:04:55,840
That’s tip number 3.

40
00:04:55,840 --> 00:05:04,944
Explain to the person things such as how long you’d like meetings to be and how often you’d like to meet.

41
00:05:04,944 --> 00:05:14,864
And, for example, if you plan to meet in person, say if you are fine with noisy places or only quieter places.

42
00:05:14,864 --> 00:05:23,680
Bryant says expressing expectations in advance will give the partnership a higher chance of going well.

43
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:28,485
But, he notes, avoid being too rigid.

44
00:05:28,485 --> 00:05:38,704
For example, if you’re hoping for Wednesday nights every week, you’ll have better luck if you state other times that also could work for you.

45
00:05:38,704 --> 00:05:45,211
Greg Scott is a Japanese-to-English translator based in Australia.

46
00:05:45,211 --> 00:05:52,032
He wrote for Lingualift.com about his early days of learning English.

47
00:05:52,032 --> 00:06:04,053
In the story, he noted that it was easier for him to have unplanned Skype meetings with his exchange partner because of his busy work schedule.

48
00:06:04,053 --> 00:06:09,509
But this plan was something both partners agreed on.

49
00:06:09,509 --> 00:06:16,832
Now, let’s say you have secured a partner and your first meeting is in a few days.

50
00:06:16,832 --> 00:06:22,096
You are ready for tip 4: prepare ahead of time.

51
00:06:22,096 --> 00:06:27,963
Before each meeting, prepare some questions on a topic of your choice.

52
00:06:27,963 --> 00:06:36,192
That will give you the chance to look up related words as well as think about your own answers.

53
00:06:36,192 --> 00:06:45,765
Preparing topics ahead of time will also help you avoid having nothing to say at your meetings, notes Bryant.

54
00:06:45,765 --> 00:06:55,200
“Otherwise, you might find yourself 10 minutes in and you’ve already gone through the ‘What do you do for a living?’ and ‘if you like to travel’ kind of questions and you have nothing else to say.”

55
00:06:55,200 --> 00:07:03,595
Or, you’ll find that you keep talking about the same things at every meeting, which you want to avoid.

56
00:07:03,595 --> 00:07:09,296
Now we move to tip 5 – focusing on communication.

57
00:07:09,296 --> 00:07:16,416
One thing to keep in mind during meetings is that the main goal is conversation practice.

58
00:07:16,416 --> 00:07:23,723
So i t’s important to let your partner speak freely, even if they make mistakes.

59
00:07:23,723 --> 00:07:32,021
Bryant recommends giving only one or two corrections after each piece of dialogue.

60
00:07:32,021 --> 00:07:42,197
Qiu says he corrects a partner only if the person is struggling to think of a word or cannot finish a sentence.

61
00:07:42,197 --> 00:07:50,027
“If they are trying to speak fluently, you don’t really want to disturb that tempo…so you just definitely keep them speaking.”

62
00:07:50,027 --> 00:07:59,083
Qui's advice to people who want to try a language exchange is simple: Don't be afraid to make mistakes!

63
00:07:59,083 --> 00:08:02,520
I’m Alice Bryant.